english:
  title: Preface to the Illustrated Exemplars of the Three Bonds
  author: Kwon Chae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There are five universal principles under heaven, and the Three Bonds stand foremost among them—truly the great law of governance and the wellspring of all transformation. Looking back to antiquity, Emperor Shun perfected the Five Canons, Tang the Victorious first established the way of men, and the Zhou house honored the Five Teachings among the people and raised up the Three Excellences. Thus we know that cultivating these bonds is the first duty of imperial rule.

    In the summer of the xinhai year of the Xuande reign, our sovereign lord commanded his ministers, saying: "The governance of the Three Dynasties all served to illuminate human relations. Yet in later ages, this instruction has grown slack, and the people lack harmony. The great bonds of ruler and subject, father and son, husband and wife—all have become obscured from their nature and grown thin. Yet there are those of extraordinary virtue and lofty integrity, unmoved by common custom, whose deeds inspire all who hear of them. I wish to gather the most exceptional of these, render them in pictures and inscriptions, and distribute them throughout the realm, so that even the simple and unlearned might easily be moved by what they see and hear, rousing their better nature. This is one path to transforming the people and establishing custom."

    Thus the sovereign appointed the Vice-Rector of the Hall of Worthies, Hyo Seongsoon, to oversee this compilation. They searched through all records, both from the Middle Kingdom and our Eastern realm, from ancient to modern times, and selected one hundred and ten exemplars each of filial sons, loyal ministers, and virtuous women worthy of remembrance. Their images were drawn before, their deeds recorded after, accompanied by verses. For the filial sons, the sacred poems on filial conduct bestowed by the Taizong Emperor were carefully preserved, together with the inscriptions of the esteemed Li Zhixian from the Filial Conduct Record compiled by the compiler's ancestor Pu. The remaining verses were composed by appointed ministers, with civil officials contributing equally to the completion. The work was named the Illustrated Exemplars of the Three Bonds, cast in type and transmitted for all ages.

    Now the sovereign commands your minister Chae to write this preface. Your minister humbly reflects: The bonds of ruler, parent, and spouse, and the ways of loyalty, filial devotion, and integrity—these flow from heaven's endowment of innate nature, common to all people. They were born when heaven and earth began, and shall not perish when heaven and earth end. They are not increased by the benevolence of Yao and Shun, nor diminished by the cruelty of Jie and Zhou. Yet in the age of virtuous kings, when the Five Canons were honored and the people lived in harmony, every household could be commended. After the Three Dynasties, peace grew rare, and the rise of rebels and traitors followed—truly because the ruler's nurture and guidance determined all.

    Our sovereign lord, possessed of sacred and luminous virtue, fulfills completely the way of ruler and teacher. With his accomplishments achieved and order established, all affairs flourish. He makes the upholding of these bonds and the maintenance of the moral order his foundation. Whatever concerns the realm of instruction receives his careful study and deliberation, becoming eternal principles. Beyond the transformation achieved through his own conduct and understanding, fearing still that the means of inspiration might be incomplete, he creates this work and spreads it among the people. Whether wise or foolish, noble or humble, child or woman—all may delight in viewing these images and learning through them, contemplating their forms, reciting the verses and grasping their meaning. None but will be moved to admiration and encouragement, their innate goodness awakened, their duties fulfilled.

    This accords with the imperial virtue of establishing and spreading the Five Canons, yet with even greater clarity and precision. Through this, the customs of the people transform beautifully, the way of governance flourishes ever more. In every home arise dutiful children, in every state faithful ministers. The songs of the South Gorge and White Flower, the verses of Broad Han and Ru Ford, shall be sung anew in the alleys and byways. The beauty of royal transformation shall yield to none, and the strength of royal achievement shall truly endure through ten thousand generations. May those who come after ever embody the sovereign's spirit, holding fast in reverence without end. Is this not right?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Bonds (Three Relationships) refer to ruler-subject, father-son, and husband-wife relationships, central to Confucian ethics.
  - key: ''
    value: The Five Canons and Five Teachings represent foundational moral principles in ancient Chinese governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Excellences mentioned here are the Six Virtues, Six Conducts, and Six Arts used in selection of worthy officials.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to 'South Gorge,' 'White Flower,' 'Broad Han,' and 'Ru Ford' are titles from the Classic of Poetry that traditionally symbolize the spread of virtuous governance.
